V{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}}\u000a{{Redirect|Hospers|the community in the midwestern United States|Hospers, Iowa}}\u000a{{Infobox Politician\u000a|name        = John Hospers\u000a|image       = John Hospers.jpg\u000a|caption     = John Hospers (1972, age 54)\u000a|birth_date  = {{birth date|1918|6|9}}\u000a|birth_place = [[Pella, Iowa|Pella]], [[Iowa]], [[United States|U.S.]]\u000a|death_date  = {{death date and age|2011|6|12|1918|6|9}}\u000a|death_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\u000a|party       = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\u000a|alma_mater  = [[Central College (Iowa)|Central College, Iowa]]<br>[[University of Iowa]]<br>[[Columbia University]]\u000a}}\u000a'''John Hospers''' (June 9, 1918 \u2013 June 12, 2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lp.org/news/press-releases/john-hospers-first-libertarian-presidential-nominee-dies-at-93 |title=John Hospers, first Libertarian presidential nominee, dies at 93 |date=June 13, 2011 |publisher=[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] (press release) |accessdate=2011-06-13}}</ref> was an American philosopher and politician.  In 1972 he became the first presidential candidate of the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]], and was the only [[minor party]] candidate to receive an electoral vote in [[United States presidential election, 1972|that year's U.S. Presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news |author-link=Jesse Walker |last=Walker |first=Jesse |date=June 13, 2011 |title=John Hospers, RIP |work=[[Reason Online]] |access-date=June 14, 2011 |url=http://reason.com/blog/2011/06/13/john-hospers-rip}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Education and career==\u000aBorn in [[Pella, Iowa]] on June 9, 1918, Hospers graduated from [[Central College (Pella, Iowa)|Central College]]. Hospers earned advanced degrees from the [[University of Iowa]] and [[Columbia University]]. He conducted research, wrote, and taught in areas of [[philosophy]], including [[aesthetics]] and [[ethics]]. He taught philosophy at [[Brooklyn College]] and at the [[University of Southern California]], where for many years he was chairman of the philosophy department and [[professor emeritus]].<ref>[http://johnhospers.com/Hospers.html "Who Is John Hospers? First Libertarian Party Presidential Candidate (1972)"], www.Johnhospers.com.</ref>\u000a\u000aIn 2002, an hour-long video about Hospers' life, work, and philosophy was released by the [[Liberty Fund]] of [[Indianapolis]], as part of its ''Classics of Liberty'' series.<ref name="hospersdvd">[http://www.libertyfund.org/details.asp?displayID=1933 ''John Hospers: The Intellectual Portrait Series''], [[Liberty Fund]].</ref>\u000a\u000a==Works==\u000aHospers' books include:<ref name="Hamowy">{{cite encyclopedia |last=Boaz |first=David |authorlink=David Boaz |editor-first=Ronald |editor-last=Hamowy |editor-link=Ronald Hamowy |encyclopedia=The Encyclopedia of Libertarianism |title=Hospers, John (1918\u2013 ) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yxNgXs3TkJYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Encyclopedia+of+libertarianism&source=bl&ots=8RVra_NxZR&sig=hOBVoAZW67v65Y7LVvcvGry0hTA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fwwYUJzCC-Gf6wGT3YCICQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=%22John%20Hospers%22&f=false  |accessdate= |edition= |year=2008 |publisher= [[SAGE Publications|SAGE]]; [[Cato Institute]] |location=Thousand Oaks, CA |isbn=978-1-4129-6580-4 |oclc=750831024 |lccn =2008009151 |page=228}}</ref>\u000a\u000a*''Meaning and Truth in the Arts'' (1946)\u000a*''Introductory Readings in Aesthetics'' (1969)\u000a*''Artistic Expression'' (1971)\u000a*''Libertarianism \u2013 A Political Philosophy for Tomorrow'' (1971)\u000a*''Understanding the Arts'' (1982)\u000a*''Law and the Market'' (1985)\u000a*''Human Conduct'' (now in its 3rd edition, 1995)\u000a*''An Introduction to Philosophical Analysis'' (now in the 4th edition, 1996)\u000a\u000aHospers was editor of three anthologies, and contributed to books edited by others. He wrote more than 100 articles in various scholarly and popular journals.<ref>{{cite book |title=Contemporary Moral Problems |publisher=[[Cengage Learning]] |last=White |first=James E. |year=2005 |page=321 |isbn=9780534584306 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ojsdcVGZyq8C&pg=PA321&dq=%22John+Hospers%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=UhIYUOPVI8nr6wHau4C4CA&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22John%20Hospers%22&f=false }}</ref>\u000a\u000aHospers was editor of ''The Personalist'' (1968\u20131982) and ''[[The Monist]]'' (1982\u20131992),<ref name="Hamowy"/> and was a senior editor at ''[[Liberty (1987)|Liberty]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news |author-link=Stephen D. Cox |last=Cox |first=Stephen |title=John Hospers, R.I.P. |work=[[Liberty (1987)|Liberty]] |date=June 17, 2011 |access-date=July 31, 2012 |url=http://www.libertyunbound.com/node/587}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Friendship with Ayn Rand==\u000aDuring the period he taught philosophy at Brooklyn College, Hospers was very interested in [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivism]]. He appeared on [[Talk radio|radio shows]] with [[Ayn Rand]], and devoted considerable attention to her ideas in his ethics textbook ''Human Conduct''.<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Letters of Ayn Rand]] |publisher=[[E.P. Dutton|Dutton]] |last=Rand |first=Ayn |editor-last=Berliner |editor-first=Michael S. |year=1995 |pages=502\u2013564 |isbn=0-525-93946-6}}</ref>\u000a\u000aAccording to Rand's biographer, [[Barbara Branden]], Hospers met Rand when she addressed the student body at Brooklyn College.  They became friends, and had lengthy philosophical conversations.  Rand's discussions with Hospers contributed to her decision to write [[nonfiction]].  Hospers read ''[[Atlas Shrugged]]'' ([[1957 in literature|1957]]), which he considered an aesthetic triumph.<ref>Hospers, John. [http://www.objectivistliving.com/forums/index.php?s&showtopic=1389&view=findpost&p=13583 ''Atlas Shrugged'': A Twentieth Anniversary Tribute], ''Libertarian Review'', Vol. VI, No. 6, October 1977.</ref>  Although Hospers became convinced of the validity of Rand's [[Morality|moral]] and [[Ideology|political]] views, he disagreed with her about issues of [[epistemology]], the subject of their extensive correspondence.<ref>{{cite book | title= [[The Passion of Ayn Rand]] |publisher=[[Doubleday & Company]] | author= [[Barbara Branden|Branden, Barbara]] |year= 1986 | pages= 323\u2013324, 413 |isbn= 0-385-19171-5}}</ref>  Rand broke with Hospers after he criticized her talk on "''Art and Sense of Life''", before the American Society of Aesthetics at [[Harvard University|Harvard]].<ref>Branden, Barbara, ''The Passion of Ayn Rand''. ibid. p. 324.</ref>\u000a\u000a==1972 presidential candidacy==\u000aIn the [[United States presidential election, 1972|1972 U.S. Presidential election]], Hospers and [[Tonie Nathan]] were the first presidential and vice-presidential nominees, respectively, of the newly formed Libertarian Party.<ref name="Hamowy"/> The Libertarian Party was poorly organized, and Hospers and Nathan managed to get on the ballot in only two states<ref name="Dionne">[[E. J. Dionne|Dionne, E. J.]] ''Why Americans Hate Politics''. New York: [[Simon & Schuster]], 1991. p. 269. ISBN 978-0-671-68255-2</ref> ([[Washington state|Washington]] and [[Colorado]]), receiving 3,674 popular votes.<ref name="leip">[http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1972&f=0&off=0&elect=0 "1972 Presidential General Election Results"], Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections.</ref>\u000a\u000aHospers and Nathan received one [[U.S. Electoral College|electoral vote]] from [[faithless elector]] [[Roger MacBride]], a [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] from [[Virginia]], resulting in Nathan becoming the first woman to receive an electoral vote in a United States presidential election.<ref name="Dionne"/><ref>{{cite book | title=[[Radicals for Capitalism: A Freewheeling History of the Modern American Libertarian Movement]] | publisher=[[PublicAffairs]] | author=[[Brian Doherty (journalist)|Doherty, Brian]] | year=2008 | pages=392\u2013393 | isbn=9781586485726}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a* [[American philosophy]]\u000a* [[List of American philosophers]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{reflist|30em}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a{{Wikiquote}}\u000a* [http://johnhospers.com/ JohnHospers.com]\u000a* {{C-SPAN|johnhospers}}\u000a* {{FAG|71700427|Dr John Hospers}}\u000a* {{Goodreads author}}\u000a\u000a{{s-start}}\u000a{{s-ppo}}\u000a{{s-new|first}}\u000a{{s-ttl|title=[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] [[List of United States Libertarian Party presidential tickets|nominee]] for [[President of the United States]]|years=[[United States presidential election, 1972|1972]]}}\u000a{{s-aft|after=[[Roger MacBride]]}}\u000a{{s-end}}\u000a\u000a{{LibertarianPresidentialNominees}}\u000a{{United States presidential election, 1972}}\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Hospers, John}}\u000a[[Category:1918 births]]\u000a[[Category:2011 deaths]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\u000a[[Category:American academics]]\u000a[[Category:American book editors]]\u000a[[Category:American classical liberals]]\u000a[[Category:American libertarians]]\u000a[[Category:American magazine editors]]\u000a[[Category:American male writers]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American political philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American political writers]]\u000a[[Category:Brooklyn College faculty]]\u000a[[Category:California Libertarians]]\u000a[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Determinists]]\u000a[[Category:Libertarian Party (United States) presidential nominees]]\u000a[[Category:Libertarian theorists]]\u000a[[Category:Members of the Libertarian Party (United States)]]\u000a[[Category:People from Pella, Iowa]]\u000a[[Category:United States presidential candidates, 1972]]\u000a[[Category:University of Southern California faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Writers from California]]\u000a[[Category:Writers 